  "title": "Rationing Antiretroviral Therapy in Africa — Treating Too Few, Too Late",
  "abstract": "The standard approach to HIV treatment in Africa is to wait until people are visibly sick, treat them with effective but poorly tolerated drugs, and then wait until they are sick again before switching regimens. Nathan Ford, Edward Mills, and Dr. Alexandra Calmy write that there are several problems with this approach.",
